The days of palmy prosperity are not those most favorable to the display
of public virtue or the influence of wise and good men. In hard, doubtful,
unprosperous, and dangerous times, the disinterested and patriotic find
their way, by a species of public instinct, unopposed, joyfully welcomed,
to the control of affairs.
